body:
The code refuse to compile, though there is no other references existing at the point, technically.
Using the rust stable 1.69.

```rust
fn main() {
    pub fn fx<'a, T: 'a, U>(_: &mut &'a mut T) ->fn(&mut &'a U) {
        fn x1<'b, T: 'b>(_: &mut &'b T) {}
        x1::<U>
    }

    let mut b = &mut 1;
    let n = {
        let c = &mut b;
        let f = fx(c);

        let mut n = &*c;
        f(&mut n);

        n
    };
    drop(n);

    println!("{}", b); // fails to compile
}
```

reporting 
```
   |
45 |         let mut c = &mut b;
   |                     ------ mutable borrow occurs here
...
56 |     println!("{}", b);
   |                    ^
   |                    |
   |                    immutable borrow occurs here
   |                    mutable borrow later used here
   |
   = note: this error originates in the macro `$crate::format_args_nl` which comes from the expansion of the macro `println` (in Nightly builds, run with -Z macro-backtrace for more info)
```

**Updated 1:**
_found a reasonable explanation for the following, it is not a problem._
_But the problem above still holds._

**Updated 2:** 
 _The problem is effectively because of a reborrowing of b, introduced by `let mut n = &*c`, having a scope not less than `b`'s. _
 _As a result, anytime b is accessed (e.g. b is alive),  the reborrowing is alive too,  and b is shadowed by the reborrowing._
  
 _It is hard to say it's a bug or not, but it does be confusing in this case._
 _I think it may be the reason why `*(&'short mut  &'long mut ref)  ---> &'short mut ref`_

Another representation of the same root cause, some implicit lifetime, bring in by c, I guess.

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut a = 1;
    let mut b = &mut a;

    let n = {
        let mut c = &mut b;
        let mut n = &*c;  // ---------------> let's qualified it to &'long *c
        drop(c);  // -----------------------> fails to compile
        n
    };  // ---------------------------------> c drops here ok
    
    println!("{}", n);  // ----------------> 'long extends here at least
}
```
